Alan has had a lifelong policy

01:25:01.530 --> 01:25:04.230
of only representing somebody once.

01:25:04.230 --> 01:25:05.490
Never twice.

01:25:05.490 --> 01:25:06.870
Why?

01:25:06.870 --> 01:25:09.720
Because he never wanted to be
house counsel to the mafia.

01:25:12.180 --> 01:25:15.990
So, he early on had this position.

01:25:15.990 --> 01:25:18.030
He only represents somebody once.

01:25:18.030 --> 01:25:22.230
The mafia wants a lawyer
who's an in-house counsel

01:25:22.230 --> 01:25:24.453
who represents them in all their cases.

01:25:25.500 --> 01:25:28.860
So, that's the reason and
Alan never publicly explained

01:25:28.860 --> 01:25:31.110
that I know it's a fact,
'cause I've known him

01:25:31.110 --> 01:25:33.920
from the day that we met at
Harvard Law School in 1964.

01:25:33.920 --> 01:25:36.060
He was a first-year professor.

01:25:36.060 --> 01:25:37.650
I was a first-year student.

01:25:37.650 --> 01:25:40.443
We both had Brooklyn
accents and we hit it off.

01:25:41.400 --> 01:25:43.500
We've been close friends, ever since.

01:25:43.500 --> 01:25:45.810
- So there's some kind of
unethical line that's crossed

01:25:45.810 --> 01:25:49.320
when you continuously represent a client.

01:25:49.320 --> 01:25:52.650
- Yeah. He thought it was
not so much an ethical line.

01:25:52.650 --> 01:25:55.260
You have a right to
represent mafia people,

01:25:55.260 --> 01:25:56.910
but he didn't want to be house counsel.

01:25:56.910 --> 01:26:00.990
He didn't want to have
them ask him for advice,

01:26:00.990 --> 01:26:02.883
in advance of what they were doing.

01:26:04.041 --> 01:26:06.090
He was willing to represent somebody once,

01:26:06.090 --> 01:26:07.740
no matter how awful.

01:26:07.740 --> 01:26:11.220
Claus von Bulow was accused
of killing his wife.

01:26:11.220 --> 01:26:12.993
These are pretty nasty people.

01:26:14.670 --> 01:26:19.670
But he didn't want to be
house counsel to any of them.

01:26:19.710 --> 01:26:24.090
- So, you wrote a review of
Alan Dershowitz's new book

01:26:24.090 --> 01:26:25.440
on Donald Trump.

01:26:25.440 --> 01:26:26.347
The title of that book is,

01:26:26.347 --> 01:26:28.890
"Get Trump: the Threat to Civil Liberties,

01:26:28.890 --> 01:26:32.310
Due Process and Our
Constitutional Rule of Law".

01:26:32.310 --> 01:26:35.190
Can you summarize this
book and your review of it?

01:26:35.190 --> 01:26:36.023
- Yes.

01:26:36.023 --> 01:26:38.220
By the way, I co-authored it
with my research assistant,

01:26:38.220 --> 01:26:39.720
who's sitting right here.

01:26:39.720 --> 01:26:40.983
- Emily?
- Yes.

01:26:44.310 --> 01:26:48.720
I thought that the book was
another example of the fact

01:26:48.720 --> 01:26:53.710
that everybody's entitled
to a defense and that Alan's

01:26:54.660 --> 01:26:57.360
being involved with Trump
was purely professional.

01:26:57.360 --> 01:27:00.123
It was not political. It
was not philosophical.

01:27:01.110 --> 01:27:06.000
And I thought that the fact
that he was being criticized,

01:27:06.000 --> 01:27:10.260
he was being shunned, because
of his connection to Trump,

01:27:10.260 --> 01:27:13.830
I found very interesting
that this is a guy

01:27:13.830 --> 01:27:15.543
who represented such,

01:27:18.393 --> 01:27:21.090
I'll call them distasteful figures,

01:27:21.090 --> 01:27:22.683
as Claus von Bulow,

01:27:24.030 --> 01:27:24.863
as

01:27:26.190 --> 01:27:27.363
Mike Tyson,

01:27:28.380 --> 01:27:31.110
as OJ Simpson,

01:27:31.110 --> 01:27:32.403
as Sheldon Siegel.

01:27:34.650 --> 01:27:39.317
And when he was considered
to be a skillful lawyer,

01:27:40.440 --> 01:27:42.003
made his reputation.

01:27:43.050 --> 01:27:46.110
And then he represents Donald
Trump, who to my knowledge,

01:27:46.110 --> 01:27:47.553
never killed anybody,

01:27:49.830 --> 01:27:52.500
and he's suddenly shunned.

01:27:52.500 --> 01:27:56.253
I thought the hypocrisy of
it, the political preening,

01:27:57.300 --> 01:28:00.813
was very distasteful to me.

01:28:02.580 --> 01:28:04.350
And it was not only
'cause he was my friend.

01:28:04.350 --> 01:28:07.100
If he wasn't my friend, I
think I'd have the same view.

01:28:08.760 --> 01:28:10.983
The "holier than thou" nonsense.

01:28:12.240 --> 01:28:13.743
The hypocrisy of it.

01:28:15.720 --> 01:28:18.210
They wouldn't talk to him
on Martha's Vineyard now.

01:28:18.210 --> 01:28:21.183
Alan and I are different.
I'm not so sensitive.

01:28:22.440 --> 01:28:25.170
Someone doesn't wanna
talk to me? No problem.

01:28:25.170 --> 01:28:26.673
No problem at all.

01:28:28.350 --> 01:28:33.350
But Alan, considering how
controversial his life has been,

01:28:33.480 --> 01:28:35.700
- He's somewhat sensitive.
- He's somewhat sensitive.

01:28:35.700 --> 01:28:37.747
And I've kept just telling Alan,

01:28:37.747 --> 01:28:39.630
"Alan, don't let it get to you."

01:28:39.630 --> 01:28:42.330
- Hey. I can relate, I
can definitely relate.

01:28:42.330 --> 01:28:44.190
Taking on some
controversial conversations.

01:28:44.190 --> 01:28:45.990
Still wear my heart on
my sleeve. It hurts.

01:28:45.990 --> 01:28:47.310
All of it hurts.
- Yep.

01:28:47.310 --> 01:28:49.260
- But maybe the pain makes you a better

01:28:50.340 --> 01:28:52.110
student of human nature.

01:28:52.110 --> 01:28:53.490
Maybe that's the case for him.

01:28:53.490 --> 01:28:57.450
Nevertheless, the book makes a complicated

01:28:57.450 --> 01:28:59.449
and I think an interesting point.

01:28:59.449 --> 01:29:02.497
He opens the book with,

01:29:02.497 --> 01:29:04.980
"Now that Donald Trump has
announced his candidacy

01:29:04.980 --> 01:29:08.700
for reelection as president,
the unremitting efforts

01:29:08.700 --> 01:29:11.940
by his political opponents
to, quote, get him,

01:29:11.940 --> 01:29:15.450
to stop him from running, at
any cost, will only increase.

01:29:15.450 --> 01:29:18.270
These efforts may pose the
most significant threat

01:29:18.270 --> 01:29:20.580
to civil liberty since McCarthyism."

01:29:20.580 --> 01:29:23.220
So, is he right?
- He's absolutely right.

01:29:23.220 --> 01:29:25.680
Because these attempted...

01:29:25.680 --> 01:29:28.440
For example, the prosecution,

01:29:28.440 --> 01:29:32.010
the one prosecution that has
been brought now, Alvin Bragg,

01:29:32.010 --> 01:29:33.990
in the Manhattan.

01:29:33.990 --> 01:29:34.900
I have looked at that,

01:29:34.900 --> 01:29:38.010
and I don't believe that
Trump has committed a crime,

01:29:38.010 --> 01:29:41.730
and yet Bragg was pressured to bring that.

01:29:41.730 --> 01:29:43.650
People in his office
were threatening to quit,

01:29:43.650 --> 01:29:45.030
if he didn't indict.

01:29:45.030 --> 01:29:47.493
Wholly improper, wholly unethical,

01:29:48.570 --> 01:29:50.640
and he's gonna lose the case.

01:29:50.640 --> 01:29:53.070
Has Trump committed crimes? Yes.

01:29:53.070 --> 01:29:54.723
Mostly, they're tax crimes.

01:29:57.093 --> 01:30:00.180
He has cheated on taxes, his whole career,

01:30:00.180 --> 01:30:01.830
as far as I could tell.

01:30:01.830 --> 01:30:06.830
He could easily be indicted
for state and federal taxes,

01:30:06.870 --> 01:30:09.540
but they're not as sexy.

01:30:09.540 --> 01:30:13.990
And I think that he's become a target

01:30:15.960 --> 01:30:20.400
by ambitious politicians,
ambitious prosecutors.

01:30:20.400 --> 01:30:24.510
He has gotten some sympathy,
which he doesn't deserve.

01:30:24.510 --> 01:30:28.260
and a lot of it is, pardon the phrase,

01:30:28.260 --> 01:30:30.180
political correctness.

01:30:30.180 --> 01:30:33.963
The better people are not
supposed to be Trumpers.

01:30:36.750 --> 01:30:38.923
I had an interesting
experience about Trump.

01:30:38.923 --> 01:30:41.400
I had two interesting experiences.

01:30:41.400 --> 01:30:44.440
The more recent one was
I was in the house of

01:30:45.960 --> 01:30:49.740
Lawrence Summers, the
former president of Harvard,

01:30:49.740 --> 01:30:52.470
who was driven out by political
correctness, by the way.

01:30:52.470 --> 01:30:54.813
He insulted women biologists.

01:30:56.820 --> 01:31:01.383
I was in his house when he was
still President of Harvard,

01:31:02.580 --> 01:31:07.580
when the Trump/Hillary
Clinton contest took place.

01:31:09.477 --> 01:31:11.973
And I was with Elsa.

01:31:13.560 --> 01:31:15.813
We were invited to Summers' house,

01:31:17.040 --> 01:31:18.093
in Brookline,

01:31:19.050 --> 01:31:23.790
and it looked like Hillary was gonna win,

01:31:23.790 --> 01:31:26.850
and the Harvard faculty members,
they were all celebrating,

01:31:26.850 --> 01:31:29.490
they were all figuring out
what their cabinet positions

01:31:29.490 --> 01:31:31.890
were gonna be, blah,
blah, blah, blah, blah.

01:31:31.890 --> 01:31:34.140
And then, at about 11:30 at night,

01:31:34.140 --> 01:31:36.000
all of a sudden, it was announced that,

01:31:36.000 --> 01:31:37.950
in terms of electoral votes,

01:31:37.950 --> 01:31:41.070
Trump had just eked out of a victory.

01:31:41.070 --> 01:31:43.410
That Hillary beat him in the popular vote,

01:31:43.410 --> 01:31:48.060
but he had won the electoral college,

01:31:48.060 --> 01:31:50.973
and there was an immediate depression.

01:31:54.570 --> 01:31:56.490
- [Lex] Meaning like quiet over the room?

01:31:56.490 --> 01:31:59.763
- The room became absolutely stone-silent.

01:32:01.290 --> 01:32:05.460
And they were all, you know, disappointed.

01:32:05.460 --> 01:32:07.500
Well, that was a memorable moment.

01:32:07.500 --> 01:32:10.140
And it told me that

01:32:10.140 --> 01:32:12.423
they were a little bit too overconfident.

01:32:13.560 --> 01:32:16.330
They were savoring

01:32:17.340 --> 01:32:20.163
being part of a
presidential administration.

01:32:21.330 --> 01:32:22.923
Ambition had been thwarted.

01:32:24.120 --> 01:32:27.570
I'm not a great fan of preening ambition.

01:32:27.570 --> 01:32:30.360
I think it blinds people to realities.

01:32:30.360 --> 01:32:32.550
- [Lex] And the resulting
arrogance from such ambition.

01:32:32.550 --> 01:32:34.530
- And the arrogance, yes.

01:32:34.530 --> 01:32:37.770
It's one of the reasons I
didn't accept Jim Vorenberg's

01:32:37.770 --> 01:32:40.260
offer to be part of
the academic community.

01:32:40.260 --> 01:32:41.580
I mean, I represent professors,

01:32:41.580 --> 01:32:42.870
I had friends who were professors.

01:32:42.870 --> 01:32:45.570
I represent students, I have
friends who are students,

01:32:47.040 --> 01:32:50.460
and I have a great
regard for universities,

01:32:50.460 --> 01:32:51.873
and higher education.

01:32:53.040 --> 01:32:55.650
But I was not about to
become part of the culture.

01:32:55.650 --> 01:32:57.810
I thought that it was not good for me,

01:32:57.810 --> 01:33:01.200
and not good for the institution, either.

01:33:01.200 --> 01:33:02.940
- A culture that can breed arrogance.

01:33:02.940 --> 01:33:04.740
- Yes.
- Self importance.

01:33:04.740 --> 01:33:06.210
- [Harvey] Yep.

01:33:06.210 --> 01:33:07.890
- And I, in a sense,

01:33:07.890 --> 01:33:11.460
the election of Donald Trump
was a big F.U. to such-

01:33:11.460 --> 01:33:12.450
- Correct.

01:33:12.450 --> 01:33:14.430
Which is why I think he,

01:33:14.430 --> 01:33:18.033
why I think he managed to pull it off.

01:33:19.230 --> 01:33:20.820
- To jump topics a little bit,

01:33:20.820 --> 01:33:24.090
what do you think about
something you've written about,

01:33:24.090 --> 01:33:26.490
what do you think about the
mass surveillance programs

01:33:26.490 --> 01:33:30.090
by the NSA and also probably
by other organizations,

01:33:30.090 --> 01:33:32.373
CIA, FBI, and others?

01:33:33.630 --> 01:33:36.540
And broadly, what do you think about

01:33:36.540 --> 01:33:40.020
the importance of privacy
for the American citizen?

01:33:40.020 --> 01:33:40.853
- Okay.

01:33:40.853 --> 01:33:44.340
I believe that the FBI

01:33:44.340 --> 01:33:45.603
should be abolished.

01:33:46.950 --> 01:33:50.580
'Cause I believe that its
culture was so corrupted

01:33:50.580 --> 01:33:53.190
by its first director,

01:33:53.190 --> 01:33:55.740
John Edgar Hoover,

01:33:55.740 --> 01:33:57.183
J. Edgar Hoover,

01:33:58.110 --> 01:34:02.610
that it is impossible to reform the FBI

01:34:02.610 --> 01:34:05.403
to make its agents honest,

01:34:06.810 --> 01:34:09.720
to force them to obey the constitution.

01:34:09.720 --> 01:34:13.413
The First, Fourth and Fifth
amendments, especially.

01:34:16.020 --> 01:34:19.143
And it's a culture that cannot be changed.

01:34:20.490 --> 01:34:25.290
Hoover established the culture
and no FBI director since

01:34:25.290 --> 01:34:26.643
has been able to change it.

01:34:27.780 --> 01:34:29.910
If you go online,

01:34:29.910 --> 01:34:33.750
I did, on YouTube, a video,

01:34:33.750 --> 01:34:35.730
for the ACLU of Massachusetts.

01:34:35.730 --> 01:34:37.080
It was when I was on the board.

01:34:37.080 --> 01:34:39.060
It was probably when I was
president of the board.

01:34:39.060 --> 01:34:41.250
I was president of the
board for two years.

01:34:41.250 --> 01:34:44.370
I was on the board for 20 years.

01:34:44.370 --> 01:34:45.280
And I did

01:34:46.483 --> 01:34:50.190
a video about advising
people to never, ever,

01:34:50.190 --> 01:34:51.990
ever talk to an FBI agent,

01:34:51.990 --> 01:34:54.510
when they come knocking on your door.

01:34:54.510 --> 01:34:58.050
- Can you briefly explain the intuition

01:34:58.050 --> 01:34:59.103
why not to talk to an FBI agent?

01:34:59.103 --> 01:35:01.380
- They have a system.

01:35:01.380 --> 01:35:03.960
When they come in and interview you,

01:35:03.960 --> 01:35:06.243
two agents show up, never one.

01:35:07.320 --> 01:35:10.260
One asks the question.
The other one takes notes.

01:35:10.260 --> 01:35:12.510
The note-taking agent
takes notes and it goes

01:35:12.510 --> 01:35:17.510
back to the office and types
up a report called a Form 302,

01:35:18.060 --> 01:35:23.060
which is the official record
of what was asked and answered.

01:35:25.980 --> 01:35:29.253
So, when I have a client
interviewed by the FBI,

01:35:30.270 --> 01:35:31.143
I show up,

01:35:32.430 --> 01:35:37.430
and I always agree, almost
always agree to the interview.

01:35:40.020 --> 01:35:41.493
But I bring a tape recorder.

01:35:42.930 --> 01:35:45.090
And I say, "All right,
I'm gonna tape this."

01:35:45.090 --> 01:35:47.460
And they say, "Well, by regulation,

01:35:47.460 --> 01:35:50.060
we're not allowed to do the
interview if it's taped.

01:35:51.120 --> 01:35:55.620
The record is the 302,
the agent's taking notes."

01:35:55.620 --> 01:35:58.890
I say, "Well, I have a policy, too.

01:35:58.890 --> 01:36:01.830
My policy is to never allow
a client to be interviewed,

01:36:01.830 --> 01:36:03.123
unless it's recorded.

01:36:03.960 --> 01:36:05.580
So, it's unfortunate,

01:36:05.580 --> 01:36:07.410
but we're gonna have to end this meeting."

01:36:07.410 --> 01:36:09.243
And the agents get up and leave.

01:36:11.190 --> 01:36:15.240
And I have never seen a Form 302

01:36:15.240 --> 01:36:17.580
that I consider to be accurate.

01:36:17.580 --> 01:36:22.580
The agents write down what
they wish you had said.

01:36:23.160 --> 01:36:24.630
Rather than what you said.

01:36:24.630 --> 01:36:28.740
It is a wholly corrupt organization

01:36:28.740 --> 01:36:31.620
that has not gotten any
better since Hoover died.

01:36:31.620 --> 01:36:35.580
- [Lex] And fundamentally, the
corruption is in the culture

01:36:35.580 --> 01:36:40.580
that is resisting the
Constitution of the United States.

01:36:40.980 --> 01:36:42.600
The First and Fourth and Fifth amendments.

01:36:42.600 --> 01:36:46.157
- Correct. It's not financial corruption.

01:36:46.157 --> 01:36:49.533
It is corruption of the mission.

01:36:50.610 --> 01:36:53.430
And I think it should be abolished.

01:36:53.430 --> 01:36:56.700
And if we need a federal
investigative agency,

01:36:56.700 --> 01:37:00.943
it should be a new name, a new
culture, wholly new members,

01:37:00.943 --> 01:37:02.163
a new director.

01:37:03.510 --> 01:37:05.940
It's impossible

01:37:05.940 --> 01:37:08.310
to reform the FBI.

01:37:08.310 --> 01:37:11.220
- Can you elaborate on what
exactly is broken about the FBI?

01:37:11.220 --> 01:37:14.670
Is it the famous saying,

01:37:14.670 --> 01:37:18.180
from Stalin's KGB head,

01:37:18.180 --> 01:37:20.610
Beria, "Show me the man and
I'll show you the crime"?

01:37:20.610 --> 01:37:23.070
- Right.
- Is it that kind of process?

01:37:23.070 --> 01:37:24.270
- It's that kind of process.

01:37:24.270 --> 01:37:27.270
They decide who's guilty and
then they go about concocting

01:37:27.270 --> 01:37:31.770
a case against a person
who they want to get.

01:37:31.770 --> 01:37:35.220
- [Lex] So, the goal is
not to find the truth or-

01:37:35.220 --> 01:37:37.800
- It's to solve the case and close it,

01:37:37.800 --> 01:37:40.620
and enhance their reputations.

01:37:40.620 --> 01:37:43.890
- But to show that an
innocent man is guilty

01:37:43.890 --> 01:37:47.013
is also solving the case,
from their perspective.

01:37:47.910 --> 01:37:50.880
So, to falsely convict,

01:37:50.880 --> 01:37:53.460
or falsely imprison an innocent man

01:37:53.460 --> 01:37:55.560
is also solving the case.

01:37:55.560 --> 01:37:56.900
- Well, it closes the case,

01:37:56.900 --> 01:37:59.820
if they falsely imprison an innocent man.

01:37:59.820 --> 01:38:02.370
They're interested in closing cases.

01:38:02.370 --> 01:38:05.100
- So, that's the FBI, but broadly speaking

01:38:05.100 --> 01:38:07.200
about the surveillance aspect of this,

01:38:07.200 --> 01:38:11.010
what are your views on the right

01:38:11.010 --> 01:38:13.800
that an American citizen has to privacy?

01:38:13.800 --> 01:38:18.270
- Well, wire tapping and
electronic surveillance

01:38:18.270 --> 01:38:20.313
are very, very intrusive.

01:38:21.330 --> 01:38:25.270
And I think that the circumstance

01:38:26.610 --> 01:38:28.923
that these tools are
used should be narrowed.

01:38:30.150 --> 01:38:33.093
For example, they're used
in a lot of drug cases.

01:38:33.930 --> 01:38:36.840
Since I don't think drugs
should be illegal in any event,

01:38:36.840 --> 01:38:40.480
I certainly think that it's a
terrible violation of privacy

01:38:43.050 --> 01:38:45.423
to use wire tapping in a drug case.

01:38:46.560 --> 01:38:49.323
I could see it in cases of murder,

01:38:51.510 --> 01:38:55.443
possibly in cases of serious extortion,

01:38:56.370 --> 01:39:00.660
but on other kinds of kinds
of crimes where they wire tap,

01:39:00.660 --> 01:39:02.100
especially drug cases,

01:39:02.100 --> 01:39:04.473
I believe drugs should
all be legalized anyway,

01:39:06.000 --> 01:39:06.950
I think it's...

01:39:09.420 --> 01:39:12.363
The price we pay as
society is not worth it.

01:39:13.710 --> 01:39:17.520
- On the Wikipedia page for
"Nothing to hide", you're cited.

01:39:17.520 --> 01:39:18.997
In fact, your book that you gave me today,

01:39:18.997 --> 01:39:21.420
"Three Felonies A Day", is cited.

01:39:21.420 --> 01:39:22.830
So, "nothing to hide" argument.

01:39:22.830 --> 01:39:26.673
That's an argument that if
you're a well-behaved citizen,

01:39:27.600 --> 01:39:28.680
you have nothing to hide,

01:39:28.680 --> 01:39:31.020
and therefore your
privacy can be violated.

01:39:31.020 --> 01:39:34.533
- Well, the problem is that
under the federal criminal code,

01:39:36.150 --> 01:39:38.100
particularly the federal criminal code,

01:39:40.500 --> 01:39:43.980
it is very easy to be
charged with a crime.

01:39:43.980 --> 01:39:44.813
Now, why?

01:39:46.860 --> 01:39:49.110
Under the Constitution,

01:39:49.110 --> 01:39:51.090
the Federal Government does not have

01:39:51.090 --> 01:39:54.210
plenary criminal jurisdiction.

01:39:54.210 --> 01:39:55.503
That's up to the state.

01:39:57.360 --> 01:40:00.900
How is it that the feds indict,

01:40:00.900 --> 01:40:03.213
in so many areas of American life?

01:40:04.320 --> 01:40:07.860
It's because the Supreme Court
has allowed the following

01:40:07.860 --> 01:40:12.063
absolutely insane situation to prevail.

01:40:13.920 --> 01:40:16.560
Anything can be made a federal crime,

01:40:16.560 --> 01:40:20.223
if, in the course of the
commission of the crime,

01:40:21.630 --> 01:40:26.630
the means of interstate
communication or travel are used.

01:40:28.500 --> 01:40:30.930
That means that if you commit a crime,

01:40:30.930 --> 01:40:34.110
which ordinarily would be a state crime,

01:40:34.110 --> 01:40:37.683
and you use the telephone
or you send a letter,

01:40:38.580 --> 01:40:40.323
it suddenly becomes federal.

01:40:41.430 --> 01:40:45.390
That means that the limitation
that the founding fathers

01:40:45.390 --> 01:40:48.900
who wrote the Constitution intended

01:40:48.900 --> 01:40:52.840
to keep the feds out of daily life

01:40:53.880 --> 01:40:56.820
and to give that jurisdiction to the state

01:40:56.820 --> 01:40:59.220
has been completely thwarted.

01:40:59.220 --> 01:41:03.600
'Cause I can't think of the a case

01:41:03.600 --> 01:41:06.270
where somebody doesn't use a telephone,

01:41:06.270 --> 01:41:07.780
in the course of

01:41:09.150 --> 01:41:13.173
planning, discussing something
that's arguably criminal.

01:41:14.040 --> 01:41:18.213
And so this limited authority,
the federal government,

01:41:20.550 --> 01:41:25.550
to bring charges in
criminal cases, is illusory.

01:41:26.310 --> 01:41:28.413
The feds can indict a ham sandwich.

01:41:29.430 --> 01:41:32.013
- So basically, everybody's
guilty, and if the,

01:41:34.142 --> 01:41:36.390
if the feds wanna bring you in, they can.

01:41:36.390 --> 01:41:37.560
They can find a way.
- Correct.

01:41:37.560 --> 01:41:42.560
And that allows them to terrorize
people who are dissidents.

01:41:42.960 --> 01:41:43.920
- Yeah.

01:41:43.920 --> 01:41:45.220
What is

01:41:46.110 --> 01:41:48.330
broken, what works, about the American

01:41:48.330 --> 01:41:50.765
criminal justice system,
from your perspective?

01:41:50.765 --> 01:41:52.200
- [Harvey] The jury system.

01:41:52.200 --> 01:41:53.880
- The jury system?
- Yes.

01:41:53.880 --> 01:41:57.390
- You like the jury system.
Everyday citizens representing-

01:41:57.390 --> 01:42:01.593
- 12 ordinary people have
to agree, unanimously,

01:42:03.060 --> 01:42:04.060
in order to convict.

01:42:05.550 --> 01:42:07.950
- What do you think about the
highest court in the land,

01:42:07.950 --> 01:42:08.880
the Supreme Court?

01:42:08.880 --> 01:42:11.130
What works and what is broken
about the Supreme Court,

01:42:11.130 --> 01:42:12.300
as an institution?

01:42:12.300 --> 01:42:13.980
What are its strengths and weaknesses?

01:42:13.980 --> 01:42:16.000
- Well, the Supreme Court is

01:42:17.580 --> 01:42:20.433
unfortunately fairly political.

01:42:21.510 --> 01:42:26.510
And the current Supreme Court
is overruling precedence,

01:42:27.480 --> 01:42:30.600
which, it's really improper.

01:42:30.600 --> 01:42:34.533
Precedence should not
be overruled so easily.

01:42:36.030 --> 01:42:40.800
It's about to overrule
the affirmative action.

01:42:40.800 --> 01:42:42.930
Now, I'm opposed to affirmative action.

01:42:42.930 --> 01:42:46.440
I think I made that clear
earlier in our discussion,

01:42:46.440 --> 01:42:49.080
but still, it's a precedent,

01:42:49.080 --> 01:42:53.010
and it should be given some respect.

01:42:53.010 --> 01:42:55.623
But in order to,

01:42:58.380 --> 01:43:02.080
in order to propagate a more conservative

01:43:03.570 --> 01:43:06.480
agenda, the court is treating precedent

01:43:06.480 --> 01:43:09.300
as if it doesn't have any role,

01:43:09.300 --> 01:43:11.763
and that's a huge mistake.

01:43:13.530 --> 01:43:16.530
Some of the congressmen
on the Democratic side

01:43:16.530 --> 01:43:19.020
are looking to enlarge the court,

01:43:19.020 --> 01:43:22.560
in order to basically do
what Franklin Roosevelt

01:43:22.560 --> 01:43:23.943
was not able to do.

01:43:26.070 --> 01:43:30.843
And that is, change
the court's philosophy.

01:43:31.800 --> 01:43:34.320
But I think that's very shortsighted,

01:43:34.320 --> 01:43:38.430
because this is a long game.

01:43:38.430 --> 01:43:40.920
This is a republic we have here.

01:43:40.920 --> 01:43:44.550
And anyone who tries to,

01:43:44.550 --> 01:43:47.310
for example, enlarge
the court from 9 to 12,

01:43:47.310 --> 01:43:51.900
in order to get more
liberals on the court,

01:43:51.900 --> 01:43:55.650
then some other administration
will try to enlarge it

01:43:55.650 --> 01:43:59.040
from 12 to 15, to get more
liberals on the court.

01:43:59.040 --> 01:43:59.873
You'd have

01:44:01.758 --> 01:44:06.300
a constant fiddling with a
very important institution.

01:44:06.300 --> 01:44:08.430
- So the law should
have more lasting power

01:44:08.430 --> 01:44:11.400
than the political bickering of the day.

01:44:11.400 --> 01:44:12.330
- Correct.

01:44:12.330 --> 01:44:17.330
- Let me ask you, you've
lived one heck of a life,

01:44:17.460 --> 01:44:21.450
and fought a lot of battles
and you continue to do so,

01:44:21.450 --> 01:44:23.487
with the Harvard Board of Overseers.

01:44:23.487 --> 01:44:26.883
So, first of all, thank
you for that, but uh,

01:44:28.140 --> 01:44:30.240
we're all human, we're all mortal.

01:44:30.240 --> 01:44:31.650
Do you ponder your death?

01:44:31.650 --> 01:44:33.930
Do you ponder your mortality?
Are you afraid of it?

01:44:33.930 --> 01:44:37.230
- Well, let me say this.
My father died at 48.

01:44:37.230 --> 01:44:38.670
He died 'cause he smoked.

01:44:38.670 --> 01:44:42.510
He died at 48 because he smoked
four packs of Camels a day.

01:44:42.510 --> 01:44:45.270
He got a massive heart attack at 43.

01:44:45.270 --> 01:44:48.990
He continued to smoke, despite that.

01:44:48.990 --> 01:44:52.500
He died at 48. So, I did not
expect to live this long.

01:44:52.500 --> 01:44:53.760
'Cause I thought it was genetic.

01:44:53.760 --> 01:44:55.443
It turns out it was cigarettes.

01:44:56.430 --> 01:45:00.523
So, here I am, I'm
gonna be 81 on May 10th.

01:45:00.523 --> 01:45:02.550
I was born on May 10th, 1942,

01:45:02.550 --> 01:45:05.103
which is Mother's Day, coincidentally,

01:45:06.600 --> 01:45:09.690
and I realize I'm not gonna live forever.

01:45:09.690 --> 01:45:14.690
I also take pride in the
fact that I have demonstrated

01:45:15.000 --> 01:45:17.580
that a lawyer does not
have to go with a law firm,

01:45:17.580 --> 01:45:19.620
in order to manage to make it.

01:45:19.620 --> 01:45:22.980
You can make your own, write
your own, what's the word?

01:45:22.980 --> 01:45:24.093
Write your own ticket.

01:45:25.710 --> 01:45:26.583
I've done that.

01:45:28.920 --> 01:45:32.010
I agree that I've had an elite education.

01:45:32.010 --> 01:45:34.890
I went to Princeton
and Harvard Law School.

01:45:34.890 --> 01:45:36.720
But I don't think you have to necessarily

01:45:36.720 --> 01:45:40.020
go to elite institutions
in order to really make it.

01:45:40.020 --> 01:45:41.253
You need to work hard.

01:45:42.240 --> 01:45:44.370
But you shouldn't put
yourself in a place where

01:45:44.370 --> 01:45:48.210
you're not gonna feel
comfortable and what's the word?

01:45:48.210 --> 01:45:49.043
Empowered?

01:45:49.043 --> 01:45:52.390
Like I refused to take Vorenberg's

01:45:54.060 --> 01:45:57.303
invitation for tenure track
position at Harvard Law School.

01:46:02.760 --> 01:46:06.963
I'll tell you one other
story that illustrates this.

01:46:08.160 --> 01:46:09.840
I was originally pre-med.

01:46:09.840 --> 01:46:12.510
My freshman-sophomore years at Princeton,

01:46:12.510 --> 01:46:14.160
I was in the pre-med program.

01:46:14.160 --> 01:46:14.993
Why?

01:46:15.930 --> 01:46:17.380
Because my parents

01:46:18.360 --> 01:46:22.683
wanted me to marry the daughter
of our family physician.

01:46:24.180 --> 01:46:28.647
And the idea was I was
gonna go to medical school

01:46:28.647 --> 01:46:31.350
and I was gonna go into
medical practice with him

01:46:31.350 --> 01:46:33.033
in Hackensack, New Jersey.

01:46:35.070 --> 01:46:37.170
We had moved from Brooklyn at the time.

01:46:37.170 --> 01:46:39.390
Long story why we had
to move from Brooklyn.

01:46:39.390 --> 01:46:42.240
It had to do with my
father's having a problem

01:46:42.240 --> 01:46:44.890
with the Furies Union and
having his life threatened.

01:46:46.410 --> 01:46:47.807
And we moved to Maywood, New Jersey,

01:46:47.807 --> 01:46:51.513
'cause he got a job in a fur
shop in Passaic, New Jersey.

01:46:52.950 --> 01:46:55.950
And a family physician,
they had three daughters,

01:46:55.950 --> 01:46:58.380
the oldest of whom was my age.

01:46:58.380 --> 01:47:00.130
She went to Hackensack High School.

01:47:01.050 --> 01:47:03.120
I went to Pagoda High School.

01:47:03.120 --> 01:47:05.373
They're both in North Burton County.

01:47:06.990 --> 01:47:11.990
And the idea was that she
and I were gonna marry,

01:47:12.000 --> 01:47:16.620
I was gonna go to medical
school, I was going to become

01:47:16.620 --> 01:47:19.110
a partner of her father,

01:47:19.110 --> 01:47:21.153
in his medical practice in Hackensack.

01:47:22.080 --> 01:47:25.210
When he retired, I was
gonna inherit the practice.

01:47:25.210 --> 01:47:28.767
This scenario was concocted
by Carolyn's mother,

01:47:28.767 --> 01:47:29.823
and my mother.

01:47:32.370 --> 01:47:35.940
In my sophomore year at Princeton,

01:47:35.940 --> 01:47:39.120
I won a fellowship to spend that summer

01:47:39.120 --> 01:47:42.090
between my sophomore and
junior year in Paris.

01:47:42.090 --> 01:47:43.473
I was fluent by then.

01:47:44.670 --> 01:47:47.100
I had taken an accelerated French course,

01:47:47.100 --> 01:47:48.723
my freshman-sophomore year.

01:47:50.130 --> 01:47:52.473
And I went to Paris.

01:47:53.708 --> 01:47:55.708
It was my first time out of the country.

01:47:59.430 --> 01:48:02.733
I spent the entire summer working,

01:48:03.900 --> 01:48:06.600
supporting myself there,
first to pay the airfare,

01:48:06.600 --> 01:48:08.890
and I earned money

01:48:09.930 --> 01:48:11.133
for room and board.

01:48:13.124 --> 01:48:15.870
And I thought about my life
and I decided, number one,

01:48:15.870 --> 01:48:19.260
I didn't want to be a physician,
I wanted to be a lawyer.

01:48:19.260 --> 01:48:22.173
Number two, I didn't
want to marry Carolyn.

01:48:23.580 --> 01:48:27.633
And I came back, I changed
from pre-med to pre-law.

01:48:28.680 --> 01:48:30.930
I broke up with Carolyn,

01:48:30.930 --> 01:48:33.600
who was, by that time,
at school at Douglas,

01:48:33.600 --> 01:48:34.980
right down the road from Princeton.

01:48:34.980 --> 01:48:36.123
She had followed me.

01:48:38.010 --> 01:48:39.453
Or I had followed her.

01:48:42.870 --> 01:48:45.903
My life suddenly took a
wholly different turn.

01:48:47.040 --> 01:48:50.100
So, that summer, in Paris,

01:48:50.100 --> 01:48:50.933
Paris

01:48:51.780 --> 01:48:55.773
had a outsized effect of my life.

01:48:56.700 --> 01:49:01.230
Every year, the Bravo
Theater shows "Casablanca",

01:49:01.230 --> 01:49:04.350
where Bogart has this great line.

01:49:04.350 --> 01:49:07.317
He says, "We'll always have Paris."

01:49:08.190 --> 01:49:11.340
And I think to myself, I
always used to say Elsa,

01:49:11.340 --> 01:49:14.760
we used to see "Casablanca"
every Valentine's Day,

01:49:14.760 --> 01:49:17.250
'cause it was such an
important movie to me,

01:49:17.250 --> 01:49:21.660
because Paris was
transformative in my life,

01:49:21.660 --> 01:49:23.970
and we went to Paris, every year.

01:49:23.970 --> 01:49:27.000
During my vacation, we went to Paris.

01:49:27.000 --> 01:49:31.440
That was where she took
some great pictures of Isaac

01:49:31.440 --> 01:49:32.670
where he was this high and this high,

01:49:32.670 --> 01:49:34.743
and they were hanging up in the house.

01:49:36.060 --> 01:49:38.360
And so I always...

01:49:40.080 --> 01:49:42.210
And even after Elsa's death,

01:49:42.210 --> 01:49:44.643
I've seen "Casablanca" twice now.

01:49:45.540 --> 01:49:47.493
She died in 2020.

01:49:48.810 --> 01:49:52.857
And I always think,
"We'll always have Paris."

01:49:53.767 --> 01:49:55.816
- "We'll always have Paris."

01:49:55.816 --> 01:49:57.750
(Lex breathes deeply)

01:49:57.750 --> 01:50:00.060
Well, Harvey,

01:50:00.060 --> 01:50:03.633
like I said, I hope you're
very successful in your,

01:50:04.680 --> 01:50:07.140
in your run for the
Harvard Board of Overseers.

01:50:07.140 --> 01:50:09.330
I think what you stand for,

01:50:09.330 --> 01:50:11.620
in the realm of freedom of speech is

01:50:12.810 --> 01:50:15.660
I think the thing that
makes these universities

01:50:15.660 --> 01:50:18.060
great institutions in American culture,

01:50:18.060 --> 01:50:22.140
and I'll do everything I
can to help you succeed

01:50:22.140 --> 01:50:25.170
and I just am really grateful
for all the work you've done

01:50:25.170 --> 01:50:26.880
and I'm grateful that you
would talk with me today.

01:50:26.880 --> 01:50:28.863
This was amazing. Thank you.

